The increased use of electrocautery and laser treatment
in recent years has increased the amount of exposure to
surgical smoke. Surgical smoke is called by a variety of
names, including plume, smoke plume, diathermy plume,
cautery smoke, aerosols, bioaerosols, vapors, and air con-
taminants. Smoke plumes are created when high-
temperature devices such as electrosurgical units and
LEEP equipment are used to vaporize, coagulate, or ablate
tissue, causing cellular contents to be released into the air.
The carcinogenic potential of chemicals in this smoke was
already assumed in the 1980s, and there has been
a growing interest in the potential adverse health effects
of exposure to particles in surgical smoke.
